[[Psychology]] has adapted the principles of positivist [[research]] to develop a wide range of [[laboratory]]-based approaches to research. Typically, such research seeks to test a [[hypothesis]] in controlled circumstances. In other words, all [[independent variable]]s (causes) are controlled apart from a test [[variable (math)|variable]] to investigate the effect on a [[dependent variable]] (effect).

In the simplest model, two 'treatments' (independent variables) are compared: for example, subjects are exposed to two different sound stimuli such as tones of different [[frequency|frequencies]], to compare the effects on [[heart rate]] (dependent variable). The heart rates observed are then [[statistics|analysed]] using [[inferential statistics]] such as the '[[Student's t-test|t-test]]' which can evaluate whether the differences are due to [[probability|chance]] or to the two treatments.

[[Psychologist]]s have explored many aspects of [[human]] and [[animal]] [[Behavior|behaviour]] using this kind of approach. Advantages are that the effects of [[Confounding factor|confounding variable]]s are controlled, including the influence of [[observation]] on behaviour; disadvantages are associated with the lack of relationship to the 'real world'.

