The Vancouver classification is a grading system used in [[orthopaedics]] to determine management of post-operative [[periprosthetic]] [[femur|femoral]] [[fractures]] following a [[hip arthroplasty]]. It is named for the city [[Vancouver]], home province of the [[University of British Columbia]] where the authors of the 1995 paper worked.
==Classification==
{| class="wikitable" |- ! Type ! Description ! Treatment |- | A | Fracture in the [[human trochanter|trochanteric]] region | [[ORIF]] if displaced |- | B1 | Fracture around stem or just below, with well fixed stem | [[ORIF]] with cables and plate |- | B2 | Fracture around stem or just below, with loose stem but good proximal bone | Revision of femoral component |- | B3 | Fracture around stem or just below, with poor quality or severely comminuted proximal bone | Revision of femoral component with proximal femoral replacement |- | C | Fracture below the [[Implant (medicine)|prosthesis]] | [[ORIF]] with plate |}
